{
  "answer": "**Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL III*, Chapter 48 (\"De la supériorité des peuples d’espèce caucasienne sur les peuples des autres espèces. — Des causes\").**[^1]\n\nThis chapter rebuts claims of natural Caucasian racial superiority over other races (including in the context of slavery) by noting that such a small proportion of \"Caucasian\" men dominated and harshly enslaved the vast majority of their own kind in antiquity. The key passage states:\n\n> In the republic of Athens, there were, it is assured, twenty thousand citizens and four hundred thousand slaves: that was twenty slaves for one free man, approximately the same proportion observed in the colonies between whites and blacks.[^1]\n\nComte continues by observing that great Romans owned up to five hundred or even a thousand slaves *inside the capital alone*, plus more on their domains, such that \"a twentieth of the men of the Caucasian species was therefore sufficient to maintain the other nineteen-twentieths in a servitude harsher than that to which blacks are subjected.\"[^1]\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL III*, [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-iii-ca589a/48-de-la-superiorite-des-peuples-d-espece-caucasienne/translation/#p-b496c9).",
